### Why a hard stop is required

An agent loop cold-starts on every run with no inherent awareness of how many
times it has already fired. Without an external counter in `{{STATE_PATH}}` and
a ceiling checked against that counter, nothing prevents the loop from running
indefinitely — exhausting quota, billing, or compute. The budget row in
`{{STATE_PATH}}` is the only reliable brake because it persists across cold
starts, unlike any in-memory counter the loop might maintain during a single
session.

---

## Why each worktree has its own state file

When a loop runs in parallel worktrees — for example, processing multiple
independent work items concurrently — each worktree needs its own isolated
ledger. A single shared `STATE.md` would create write conflicts as concurrent
runs try to append rows at the same time, and a partially written row could
corrupt the ledger for all workers. By giving each worktree its own copy at a
predictable path under `{{STATE_PATH}}`, each worker reads and writes
independently, and the gate-checker can aggregate across files without locking.
The trade-off is that a reconciliation step is needed at the end to merge
per-worktree results into a canonical record — but that step is safe to
automate because each input file is already complete and self-consistent.
